---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Rental Application & Background Check Platform | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How a Perth residential property manager processing 80–120 rental applications per month cut processing time from 5 days to same-day for 80% of applications with automated ID verification and tenancy database checks.",

  industry: "Real Estate",
  tags: ["Rental Applications", "Background Checks", "ID Verification", "DocuSign", "RTRA Compliance"],

  title: "Rental Application & Background Check Platform",
  summary: "A large Perth residential property manager processing up to 120 rental applications per month replaced a paper-and-PDF application process with an automated platform using OCR identity verification, tenancy database API checks, and digital lease execution — cutting processing time from five business days to same-day for 80% of complete applications.",

  heroImageDescription: "Property manager reviewing a rental application dashboard on a monitor, with identity verification status and tenancy check results visible alongside an applicant's completed digital application form",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Westshore Residential is a Perth-based property management company managing 1,100 residential properties across the northern and southern suburbs. With 18 property managers and a volume of 80 to 120 rental applications per month, the company is one of the larger independent property managers in metropolitan Perth. The business has been operating for 16 years and competes on responsiveness and the quality of its tenant placement — the ability to move qualified tenants into properties quickly is a direct competitive differentiator in the Perth rental market.",
  clientSize: "18 property managers · 1,100 properties",
  clientLocation: "Perth, WA",

  pullQuote: "We were losing good tenants to agencies who could process an application faster. Someone would apply with us and with a competitor on the same day, and the competitor would have them approved and signing a lease while we were still chasing a reference by phone. That's a real business problem in a tight market, and we fixed it.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "General Manager",
  pullQuoteRole: "Westshore Residential",

  challenge: [
    "Rental applications at Westshore arrived as PDF forms attached to emails, or as paper forms collected at open homes and posted or dropped at the office. Both formats required manual handling: paper forms were scanned, PDF attachments were saved to a shared drive, and all applications were then entered by hand into the property management software. The manual re-entry process introduced transcription errors — transposed dates of birth, truncated addresses, misspelled employer names — that sometimes only surfaced later when a credit check or tenancy database check produced unexpected results that needed to be investigated.",
    "Identity verification was conducted in person. Applicants were required to attend the office or the property manager's presence with original identity documents, which were eyeballed and photocopied. This requirement created a significant barrier for genuine applicants — particularly those applying from interstate or from properties where their current lease was expiring — and also provided less rigour than it appeared. A staff member checking a driver's licence visually has limited ability to detect a high-quality forgery, and the process created no electronic audit trail of what documents were sighted and when.",
    "Tenancy database checks — searching the TICA (Tenancy Information Centre Australasia) and NTD (National Tenancy Database) records for adverse tenancy history — were conducted through a separate web portal. Staff logged into the portal, manually entered the applicant's details, waited for the result, and then manually noted the result in the property management software. With 80 to 120 applications per month, this manual process consumed significant time. More importantly, the manual data entry between the application and the portal introduced the risk of error: entering a date of birth or previous address incorrectly could produce a clean result for an applicant who should have returned a match, or trigger a false match requiring investigation.",
    "Reference checks were conducted almost entirely by phone. Property managers called employers and previous landlords using the contact details provided by the applicant — an approach that, while standard, produced a completion rate of roughly 71%. Employers frequently didn't return calls, previous landlords were sometimes unavailable or unresponsive, and applicants who had provided incorrect contact details (deliberately or accidentally) could avoid a reference check entirely. The phone-based process also created no systematic record of what was said — notes depended on the property manager's diligence — and was time-consuming in a way that scaled poorly with application volume.",
    "The processing time problem was severe. From receipt of a complete application to an approval decision, the average time at Westshore was five business days. In the Perth rental market, where quality properties at reasonable rent attract multiple simultaneous applications, five days was often too long. The company had directly observed the pattern: a quality applicant would apply at Westshore and at a competitor, the competitor would process faster, the applicant would accept the competitor's offer, and Westshore would still be waiting on a phone reference. The general manager had a specific data point: in the previous six months, the company had experienced this outcome with at least 23 identified applicants.",
    "Compliance with the Residential Tenancies Act 1987 (WA) and the obligations under the Real Estate and Business Agents Act 1978 (WA) required specific documentation to be maintained — application records, the basis for tenancy decisions, identity verification records, and tenancy agreement execution records. The paper and email-based system produced documentation that was scattered, inconsistently formatted, and difficult to produce on demand if a tenancy decision was challenged. The company had received one formal complaint to Consumer Protection WA regarding a declined application where the applicant alleged discrimination; assembling the documentation to demonstrate the decision had been made on legitimate grounds took three staff members two days."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The decision to build a custom platform followed an 18-month period during which Westshore had evaluated and dismissed four existing rental application SaaS products operating in the Australian market, including 1Form (now managed through the REA Group) and two smaller WA-specific products. The general manager's assessment of all four was consistent: they handled application collection adequately but didn't integrate the tenancy database checks, didn't have the ID verification capability at the required standard, and created additional manual steps around reference management rather than reducing them.",
    "The referral to All Webbed Labs came through the company's PI insurer, who had been increasingly focused on the documentation and compliance aspects of tenancy decision-making and had seen other property management clients improve their compliance position through technology. The insurer's perspective — that a well-documented, automated application process reduced professional liability risk — was persuasive context for the general manager's investment case.",
    "We spent two days in the Westshore office before responding to the brief, working through a complete application cycle from receipt to approval alongside one of the senior property managers. The detailed understanding of the workflow — including the specific edge cases like co-applicants, guarantors, student applications without rental history, and interstate applications — informed a technical proposal that addressed the actual process rather than a simplified version of it. The general manager later told us that this pre-proposal investment was the main reason they chose us over a more established software vendor who had responded with a more polished but less specific proposal."
  ],

  approach: [
    "The regulatory foundation of the platform was the starting point. Western Australia's rental tenancy framework is governed by the Residential Tenancies Act 1987 (WA), supplemented by the Residential Tenancies Regulations 1989 (WA) and the Real Estate and Business Agents Act 1978 (WA). The documentation obligations under these instruments are specific: applications must be retained, decisions must be documented, and any adverse action — declining an application — must not be based on discriminatory grounds under the Equal Opportunity Act 1984 (WA). We built the data model and workflow to produce an audit-ready record for every application, not just the ones that succeeded.",
    "The identity verification component required careful vendor selection. Several ID verification services operate in the Australian market. We evaluated three: Equifax's identity verification API, IDMatrix (a subsidiary of Equifax), and a newer biometric verification provider. The decision was Equifax's verification service, which cross-references applicant-provided details (name, date of birth, address history) against credit bureau records and government datasets to confirm identity without requiring a physical document inspection. This approach met the practical identity verification standard without creating the access barrier of an in-person requirement, and produced an electronic verification record with a confidence score and the specific data points matched.",
    "AWS Textract was selected for document OCR — extracting structured data from uploaded identity documents. The use case was pre-filling application forms from uploaded documents: an applicant uploads a driver's licence, Textract extracts the name, date of birth, and address, and those fields pre-populate in the application form for the applicant to confirm. This reduced transcription errors significantly and cut application completion time for applicants. It also allowed us to capture the document image at the point of application for the audit record, replacing the in-person document inspection process.",
    "The reference check digitisation required a design decision that took some iteration. Our initial design sent referees a structured online form with the same questions a property manager would ask by phone. Testing with a group of property managers identified a problem: referees who might answer the phone and speak informally were less likely to complete a written form, particularly if they perceived it as generating a formal record. We revised the form to be shorter (five questions versus twelve), to use conversational language rather than formal HR-style phrasing, and to include a clear statement that responses were used only by the property management company and were not shared with the applicant. Completion rates in the test group moved from 47% to 73%, approaching the 71% phone completion benchmark before we went live."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The platform begins with an applicant-facing application form, accessible on desktop and mobile, that guides prospective tenants through the complete application in a single session. The form is structured in stages: personal details (pre-filled from identity document OCR where the applicant uploads their licence or passport), rental history (with referee contact details and permission to contact), employment and income (with supporting document upload for payslips or tax returns), additional applicant details (for co-applicants and guarantors), and declarations. Progress is saved automatically, allowing applicants to complete the form across multiple sessions. The average completion time for a complete application dropped to 18 minutes from an earlier baseline of 40 minutes for the paper form.",
    "Immediately on submission of a complete application, the platform triggers a four-step automated check sequence: identity verification through the Equifax API, TICA tenancy database check, NTD tenancy database check, and a credit header search. All four checks run in parallel. Results are returned in an average of four to seven minutes and are displayed in the property manager's review interface as a structured summary with colour-coded status indicators. An application that returns clean on all four checks is flagged for accelerated review — the property manager sees it at the top of their queue with a 'verification complete' status and can proceed directly to the reference check and approval decision. This is the pathway for the 80% of applications that process same-day.",
    "Reference checks are now managed through the platform's automated referee communication system. When an application is submitted, the system immediately sends structured reference request emails to each nominated referee using the contact details provided by the applicant. The emails include the property manager's name and the Westshore branding, explain what the reference is for, and link to a structured digital form. The form covers tenancy conduct, payment history, property care, and whether the referee would rent to this applicant again. Responses are captured in the platform and attached to the application record. If a referee hasn't responded within 48 hours, an automated reminder is sent. Property managers are notified when a reference response arrives.",
    "The property manager review interface consolidates everything needed to make an approval decision on a single screen: applicant details, verification results, tenancy history check results, credit header summary, reference responses, supporting documents, and the property details the application is for. The decision — approve, conditional approve (pending final reference), or decline — is recorded in the platform with a mandatory reason field for declines. This reason field, and the complete check results attached to it, form the documentary basis for responding to any complaint about a tenancy decision. Declined applications are stored with their complete record for the period required under the Real Estate and Business Agents Act.",
    "Approved applications feed directly into the lease execution workflow via DocuSign integration. The lease agreement — customised to Westshore's standard form, compliant with the Residential Tenancies Act 1987 (WA) including the prescribed terms under the Residential Tenancies Regulations — is generated automatically from the approved application data, with the correct tenancy address, commencement date, rental amount, and bond amount populated from the application record. The document is sent to all parties for electronic signature through DocuSign. Counter-signed execution copies are stored in the platform and in S3. Bond lodgement instructions and condition report scheduling are triggered on execution."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Staff review interface — complex multi-document, multi-check summary views requiring fast navigation across high application volumes" },
    { name: "FastAPI", reason: "Python-based API backend; optimal for the OCR pipeline and data science components including fraud pattern detection" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Application records, check results, audit log, and all relationship data for properties, tenancies, and parties" },
    { name: "AWS Textract", reason: "Document OCR for identity document pre-fill and digital document archiving of submitted identity records" },
    { name: "Equifax Identity Verification", reason: "Electronic identity verification against credit bureau and government datasets — replaces in-person document inspection" },
    { name: "TICA / NTD API", reason: "Automated tenancy database checks at submission — removes manual portal login and data re-entry" },
    { name: "DocuSign", reason: "Digital lease execution for all parties — legally compliant electronic signature under the Electronic Transactions Act 2011 (WA)" },
    { name: "Email Automation", reason: "Referee communication sequences, applicant status notifications, and conditional approval follow-up management" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "The implementation began with a six-week parallel running period — the new platform accepting applications alongside the old paper/PDF process, with every application processed through both systems. This parallel period served three purposes: it validated that the automated check results matched what the manual process would have found, it trained the property manager team on the new review interface with real applications rather than synthetic test cases, and it identified edge cases in the application data model that the test phase hadn't surfaced. Three meaningful edge cases emerged: overseas tenants with no Australian credit history (requiring a modified workflow with enhanced referee documentation), company-as-tenant applications for residential properties (uncommon but legally distinct under the RTA), and applications where the primary applicant was a minor, which required a guarantor and triggered specific documentation requirements.",
    "Staff training focused on the property manager review interface and the decision documentation requirements. We conducted three workshop sessions — one for each of the three PM teams grouped by portfolio — with particular emphasis on the decline documentation process. The compliance implications of a poorly documented decline decision were taken seriously by the general manager, who had been through the Consumer Protection complaint, and the property managers were receptive to the framing that the documentation tool was protecting them personally, not just the business.",
    "The TICA and NTD API integrations required formal membership agreements and data use agreements between Westshore and each database provider. These commercial agreements were Westshore's responsibility to negotiate, but we provided technical specifications to both providers to facilitate the process and were involved in the integration testing once credentials were issued. The NTD integration was straightforward. The TICA integration had one undocumented API behaviour — a specific response code for 'record found but information withheld due to age' that wasn't in the published documentation and that we had to resolve by direct contact with TICA's technical team. This added ten days to the integration timeline.",
    "The DocuSign integration required careful alignment with WA's specific requirements for residential tenancy agreements. The Residential Tenancies Act 1987 (WA) and the associated Regulations prescribe specific terms that must appear in residential tenancy agreements. We engaged the company's solicitor for a half-day review of the generated lease template to confirm that the document was compliant, that the prescribed terms were correctly incorporated, and that the electronic execution process met the requirements of the Electronic Transactions Act 2011 (WA) for the purposes of the tenancy agreement. The solicitor's review resulted in two textual amendments to the lease template but confirmed that the digital execution process was valid."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The fraud detection capability — detecting fraudulent applications — emerged organically from the data rather than from a planned design decision. Within the first month of operation, three applications were automatically flagged by a pattern-matching rule we'd built as a secondary feature: applications where the identity verification returned a mismatch on a data point that the applicant had previously submitted with a different value in a prior application through the platform. In all three cases, manual review confirmed that the applications had been submitted with fabricated or altered identity information. We hadn't expected to surface three fraud attempts in the first month. The general manager's response was to make the fraud detection capability a primary marketing point for the platform within the property owner community — owners want to know their tenant was properly screened.",
    "The applicant-facing experience required more iteration than the staff-facing experience. The property manager review interface was used by a professional team who adapted quickly and were motivated to adopt the tool. The applicant-facing application form was used by the general public, including people under significant stress who were competing for a property they needed. Two rounds of usability testing with prospective tenants recruited through social media revealed significant friction in the income documentation upload step — the instruction 'upload proof of income' produced enormous variety in what people uploaded, from bank statements to employment contracts to screenshots of their MYOB payslips. We replaced the generic instruction with a specific list of accepted documents and conditional branching based on employment type (employed, self-employed, receiving Centrelink, retired). Completion rates improved from 68% to 91%.",
    "The FastAPI choice for the backend — a departure from our more typical Node.js stack — was validated by the OCR processing pipeline requirements but added some operational overhead in the deployment configuration on AWS that we hadn't fully anticipated. The Python environment management, particularly around the AWS Textract client library versions and their transitive dependencies, required more careful configuration than a Node.js deployment would have. For future projects where the primary driver for Python is machine learning or OCR, we'd maintain the FastAPI choice; for projects where the Python capability is peripheral, the Node.js familiarity advantage is more significant than it appears in early architecture discussions."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "Four months after go-live, the platform was extended with a bond lodgement integration connecting to the Bond Administrator through the Department of Mines, Industry Regulation and Safety's online portal. Under the Residential Tenancies Act 1987 (WA), bond money must be lodged with the Bond Administrator within 14 days of receipt. The manual process of logging into the Bond Administrator portal and submitting lodgement details was automated — on lease execution, the system now queues a bond lodgement submission and confirms with the property manager when it's complete. The bond lodgement compliance rate moved from 94% to 100% within the first month of the integration.",
    "The application data, now structured and accumulated over six months, has also been used to build a predictive approval time estimate that Westshore shows applicants after submission: 'Applications like yours typically receive a decision within 4 hours.' This feature required no new external integration — it was built from the platform's own historical data. The general manager reports that it has reduced the number of applicants calling to check on their application status, because the transparency reduces anxiety during the waiting period.",
    "Westshore has begun exploring using the platform's application data — anonymised — for rental market analytics, tracking which property types attract the highest application volumes, which income bands are most active in specific suburbs, and how application-to-approval conversion rates vary by property price point. This capability was a byproduct of having structured, consistent application data rather than ad hoc PDF files, and represents the kind of value that accumulates from a well-designed data model over time."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "In the six months following full go-live, 80% of complete applications were processed within the same business day — down from an average of five business days. Reference check completion rates improved from 71% to 94% with the automated digital referee workflow. Three tenancy fraud attempts were detected and blocked in the first month alone. RTRA documentation compliance reached 100%. Application abandonment rates fell by 44% as the digital form reduced friction. Staff time per application dropped from 2.5 hours to 35 minutes.",

